 for bestpractices and # About & Help

## Overview
Develop a comprehensive About & Help documentation hub for the Gbox360 Investor Perception Index Platform. The page will provide a product overview, an FAQ with accordion behavior, an onboarding walkthrough with a step-by-step checklist for trial users, and a robust contact/support form that routes to a ticketing system. The UI should align with the fintech premium aesthetic described in the project context, ensure accessibility, and be resilient to partial data. All code must guard against null/undefined values before calling array methods and follow the runtime-safety rules specified.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A centralized Documentation hub titled “About & Help” that presents:
  - Product overview: a concise, yet rich description of Investor Perception Index (IPI) and how it integrates with the platform’s data sources (news, social, earnings transcripts) in a high-level, non-sensitive manner.
  - FAQ: an accordion-style list of frequently asked questions with expandable/collapsible answers.
  - Onboarding walkthrough: a guided onboarding section with a step-by-step trial-user checklist, contextual explanations, and progress indicators.
  - Contact support form: a form for submitting inquiries or support tickets with fields for subject, description, urgency, and optional attachments (if applicable in scope).
  - Links to API/docs: navigational anchors to developer resources and API documentation (if applicable).

Goals:
- Provide users with a clear, scannable information hub that reduces friction before onboarding and supports ongoing assistance.
- Deliver an accessible, responsive, and visually premium experience that feels aligned with Investor Perception Pro branding.
- Enable support channeling so user inquiries reach the ticketing system with structured data for triage.

Connected features and data flows:
- FAQ and onboarding content can be static or fetched from a content API; ensure safe handling of absent data.
- Contact form submission should trigger a backend API endpoint to create a support ticket and store a draft payload for auditing.
- Documentation links to API/docs (static or dynamic).
- No live dashboards or dashboards in this sprint; the focus is content delivery and a clean UX.

UI elements and guidance:
- Hero section with a large, centered heading and supportive subheading on a warm hero background, using serif headline typography and sans-serif body copy.
- Card-based sections with rounded corners, soft shadows, white surfaces, and generous padding.
- FAQ: accordion components with accessible ARIA attributes; only expose one section at a time by default or allow multiple open sections per configuration.
- Onboarding walkthrough: a vertical or horizontal stepper with each step describing actions, plus a checklist that tracks completion state and indicates progress.
- Contact form: inputs for subject, description, urgency (dropdown), and a submit button; show success/failure feedback, with proper validation and error messaging.
- Visual guidance: consistent with the visual style and color palette below; ensure adequate contrast, focus states, and keyboard navigability.

API integrations:
- No external API required for this sprint, but the architecture should be ready for integration (e.g., FAQ data source, onboarding content, and contact submission endpoints).
- If implementing with mock data, ensure the data pipeline can be swapped to real endpoints with minimal changes.

Security and accessibility:
- All interactive elements accessible via keyboard; visible focus states.
- Form inputs require validation with clear error messages and accessibility attributes (aria-live, aria-invalid, etc.).
- Ensure no runtime crashes due to null/undefined data (per runtime-safety rules).

## Components to Build
- AboutHeaderHero
  - Props: title, subtitle, backgroundPattern (optional)
  - Behavior: responsive hero with centered content; supports max width 900–1000px for hero area
- ProductOverviewCard
  - Props: overviewText, architectureSummary (non-sensitive)
  - UI: white card with rounded corners and drop shadow
- FAQAccordion
  - Props: faqItems: Array<{ id, question, answer }>
  - Behavior: accessible accordion; allow expand/collapse with ARIA attributes; guard against non-array data
- OnboardingWalkthrough
  - Props: steps: Array<{ id, title, description }>, checklist: Array<{ id, label, completed }>
  - UI: vertical or horizontal stepper; a checklist with toggles; progress indicators
- OnboardingChecklist
  - Subcomponent of OnboardingWalkthrough
  - Behavior: track completion; persist in local state or simple store; resettable
- ContactSupportForm
  - Props: onSubmit(payload)
  - Fields: subject (string), description (string), urgency (enum: Low/Medium/High)
  - Validation: required subject/description; length limits; show validation messages
  - Submission: POST to /api/support/tickets (or mock endpoint); handle success/failure states
- LinkPanel
  - Props: links: Array<{ label, href }>
  - UI: simple navigation to API/docs or related resources
- FloatingPromoCard (optional per design)
  - Props: backdropColor, ctaLabel, onCTAClick
  - Visual: brown gradient with accent orange CTA as described
- NavBar
  - Props: currentRoute, onNavigate
  - UI: logo left, centered links, actions on the right; responsive handling
- FooterNote (optional)
  - Quick links and legal notes if needed

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React with TypeScript (recommended for type safety)
- State management: local component state; global minimal store if needed for shared UI state
- Hooks: useState, useEffect, useRef as needed
- Type safety: define interfaces for data models (FAQItem, Step, TicketPayload, etc.)
- Runtime safety rules:
  - Use data ?? [] when consuming arrays from API-like sources
  - Guard array operations: (items ?? []).map(...); Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Initialize useState with correct types: useState<FAQItem[]>([]) and useState<Step[]>([]) for arrays
  - Validate API shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Optional chaining for nested data: obj?.property?.nested
  - Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
- Accessibility:
  - ARIA roles for accordion (aria-expanded, aria-controls), buttons with aria-labels
  - Form fields with proper labels, aria-invalid, and error messaging
  - Keyboard accessible navigation for all interactive elements
- Visual styling:
  - Implement the Design System visuals using CSS-in-JS (styled-components) or CSS Modules as per project norms
  - Use the provided color palette and typography guidelines
  - Card surfaces: white background, 16–20px border radius, soft shadows (0 6px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.08))
  - Hero: wide, centered content with generous padding; max width 900–1000px
  - Spacing: vertical rhythm with 24–32px gaps between sections
  - Hover/focus interactions: lift or shadow intensification for cards and CTAs
- Data handling:
  - Support data can be provided via props or mocked; ensure safe defaults when data is missing
- API placeholders:
  - For submission, implement a mock API utility that simulates POST and returns a resolved promise with success, or reject for error state; in real implementation, this will call the backend
- Routing and navigation:
  - If using a router (e.g., react-router), create routes for /about-help or equivalent; ensure links to API/docs are anchor-safe
- Performance:
  - Lazy load heavy sections if needed; ensure SSR safety if project uses SSR
- Testing considerations:
  - Unit tests for FAQAccordion behavior, OnboardingChecklist state transitions
  - End-to-end tests conceptually for form submission flow (mocked)

### Backend
- APIs to implement (if not provided by existing services):
  - POST /api/support/tickets
    - Payload: { subject: string, description: string, urgency: 'Low'|'Medium'|'High', createdBy?: string, companyId?: string }
    - Response: { id: string, status: 'received' | 'failed', createdAt: string }
  - GET /api/docs/faq (optional data source)
  - GET /api/docs/onboarding (optional data source)
- Database tables (for MVP in Sprint 1, outline):
  - tickets: id (PK), subject, description, urgency, status, created_at, created_by, company_id
  - faq_items: id, question, answer, order
  - onboarding_steps: id, title, description, order
- Validation:
  - Server-side validation for required fields
  - Rate limiting and audit logging (mocked for Sprint 1)
- Security:
  - Ensure endpoints require proper authentication/authorization if applicable; in MVP, return 401 for unauthenticated if required

### Integration
- Data flows:
  - FAQAccordion consumes FAQ data (from props or API)
  - OnboardingWalkthrough consumes steps data; state updates reflect user progress
  - ContactSupportForm posts to tickets API; handle loading, success, and error states
- Data safety:
  - Apply the runtime safety rules on all data shapes coming from APIs or store
- Theming:
  - Ensure all components read theme/colors from a centralized theme or CSS variables to guarantee consistency

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on About & Help page
   - Hero with product overview snippet and navigation to sections
2. Product Overview
   - Read concise explanation of IPI, data sources, and how it helps investors
3. FAQ
   - User expands questions to reveal answers; multiple sections may be open depending on UX choice
4. Onboarding Walkthrough
   - User sees a stepper or list of onboarding steps
   - Each step has a description; user marks steps as complete
   - A progress indicator updates; the flow guides trial users toward enabling IPI features
5. Contact Support
   - User fills Subject, Description, and Urgency
   - Validation errors shown inline
   - On submit, a ticket is created; show a success banner with ticket ID and a back-to-faq link
6. API/Docs Links
   - Users can click through to API docs or developer resources
7. Visual polish
   - Hover effects, focus rings, and responsive behavior ensure a premium feel across devices

## Technical Specifications

Data Models
- FAQItem
  - id: string
  - question: string
  - answer: string
  - order?: number
- OnboardingStep
  - id: string
  - title: string
  - description: string
  - order?: number
- TicketPayload
  - subject: string
  - description: string
  - urgency: 'Low'|'Medium'|'High'
  - createdBy?: string
  - companyId?: string
- TicketResponse
  - id: string
  - status: 'received'|'failed'
  - createdAt: string

API Endpoints
- GET /api/docs/faq
  - Returns: { data: FAQItem[] | null }
- GET /api/docs/onboarding
  - Returns: { data: OnboardingStep[] | null }
- POST /api/support/tickets
  - Body: TicketPayload
  - Response: { id: string, status: string, createdAt: string }

Security
- If authentication is required, ensure endpoints enforce auth tokens/cookies
- Validate input server-side; sanitize text
- Audit trails and raw payload preservation in sandbox for debugging

Validation
- Client-side form:
  - subject: required, 3–200 chars
  - description: required, 10–2000 chars
  - urgency: required
- FAQ data: ensure array; guard with Array.isArray and data ?? []
- Onboarding steps: ensure array and non-empty when rendering
- All array operations guarded using (data ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : []

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The About & Help page renders with hero, overview card, FAQ accordion, onboarding checklist, and contact form
- [ ] FAQ accordion supports expand/collapse with accessible ARIA attributes and no runtime crashes if data is missing
- [ ] Onboarding checklist displays steps, tracks completion in local state, and shows progress
- [ ] Contact form validates inputs, shows inline errors, and simulates ticket creation with a success message and ticket id
- [ ] All array operations guarded to prevent runtime errors due to null/undefined
- [ ] Data integration points designed to swap in real API data with minimal changes

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Follow the exact color palette and typography guidelines
- Ensure a premium fintech aesthetic with calm, trustworthy visuals
- Serif headings (Playfair Display or Georgia) and sans-serif body (Inter or Roboto)
- Card-based layout with generous spacing and soft shadows
- Interactive states: hover/focus lift, rounded surfaces, and clear CTAs
- Desktop-first layout with responsive stacking for mobile
- Accessibility and keyboard navigation throughout

Visual Style

Color Palette:
- Primary Green: #2f6f63
- Secondary Teal/Gray-Teal: #2b6250
- Neutral White: #ffffff
- Page Background Taupe: #a79e96
- Hero Beige: #f3efe6
- Text Dark: #1f1f1f
- Body Text Gray: #555555
- Card Shadow: rgba(0,0,0,0.08)
- Accent Brown (floating card): #3b2b1e
- Accent Orange (floating card CTA): #e07a4c

Typography & Layout:
- Heading: serif display font, heavy weight
- Body: sans-serif, regular to medium
- Hierarchy: large hero heading, medium subheading, small body copy
- Layout: wide hero, max content width 900–1000px, 12-column grid implied
- Spacing: large top margins on hero, line-height comfortable, 24–32px gaps

Key Design Elements
Card Design:
- Surface: white, 16–20px radius
- Shadow: 0 6px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.08)
- States: hover/focus lift
- Hierarchy: prominent CTA over muted copy

Navigation:
- White top nav, logo left, centered links, actions right
- Active/Hover: weight/underline; primary CTA green
- Responsive horizontal nav with stacking

Data Visualization:
- Not required; if added, follow neutral palette with teal/green accents

Interactive Elements:
- Buttons: rounded, green primary with white text
- Forms: light borders, rounded, teal/green focus ring
- Hover/Active: deeper color, shadow intensification

Design Philosophy
- Premium fintech aesthetic
- Clean, data-forward visuals
- Serif headlines with sans-serif body
- Clarity, accessibility, subtle depth through shadows

Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety
- Apply all six rules listed in the prompt (nullish coalescing for results, guard array methods, correct useState defaults, validate API shapes, optional chaining, destructuring with defaults)

Notes for AI development tool
- Implement components modularly with clear prop interfaces
- Use TypeScript types to enforce data contracts
- Provide sensible default data in mock implementations to avoid null references
- Ensure all data accesses are null-safe per the guidelines
- Structure code so real API integration can be swapped with minimal changes

